elements.title: Carl Cain (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that 1950s Iowa Hawkeyes men's basketball player Carl Cain (pictured) was part of the Fabulous Five, whose jerseys were all retired?

elements.title: Bewahre uns, Gott (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that "Bewahre uns, Gott" (Keep us, God) is a hymn for protection and blessing that Eugen Eckert derived from a 1968 peace song written and composed in Argentina?

elements.title: Walter Corti (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that the Pestalozzi Children's Village in Switzerland was established in 1946 after Walter Corti called for the establishment of a village for orphans of World War II?

elements.title: Ordot Dump (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that the U.S. Supreme Court ruled unanimously in favor of Guam in the territory's attempt to seek U.S. Navy contributions to clean up Ordot Dump, a former landfill and Superfund site?

elements.title: Li Qun (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that Chinese social-realist woodcut artist Li Qun felt that the works of expressionists were "far away from life"?

elements.title: Neil Simon Theatre (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that the Neil Simon Theatre, a New York City landmark, was the first Broadway theater renamed after a living playwright?

elements.title: Arti Rana (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that Arti Rana was the president of the self-help group Tharu Hath KargaGharelu Udyog when it received assistance from the World Wide Fund for Nature to make its looms more efficient?

elements.title: 2022 Turkish Masters (Wikipedia — did you know?)
elements.contents: ... that a snooker table used at the 2022 Turkish Masters was fixed with a car jack?
